Today I want to show you how we're going to make things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be able to self-assemble, self-replicating and self-healing.
So I'm going to show you what I think is the current state of manufacturing and then compare it to some natural systems.
So in the current manufacturing, we have skyscrapers -- two and a half years, half a million to a million parts, very complex, using new technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space -- five years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that fold up in 10,000 nanoseconds, and we can replicate three billion base pairs of DNA in about an hour.
That's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're very efficient, more efficient than anything we can build, more complex than anything we can build.
They are more efficient in terms of energy.
They rarely make mistakes.
They can repair themselves and live a long life.
There is something very interesting about natural systems.
If we can translate that into our built environment, there's a lot of potential in the way we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to use self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode all the complexity of what we are going to build — our buildings and machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences - basically the DNA of how our architecture works.
Then we need a programmable part that can take this sequence and use it to fold or reshape.
We need some energy to activate so that these parts of us can be folded in accordance with the program.
We need some type of error correction redundancy to ensure that we successfully build what we want.
So I'm going to show you some of the projects that my colleagues and I are working on to realize this self-assembled future.
The first two projects are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are all large-scale reconfigurable robots — 8-foot, 12-foot-long proteins.
They are embedded in electromechanical devices, sensors.
You need to decode the way you want to fold into, decode into a series of angles -- minus 120 degrees, minus 120 degrees, 0 degrees, 0 degrees, 120 degrees, minus 120 degrees, -- things like that; a series of angles, or turns, that you can wire through in that order.
Each unit gets its own message — say minus 120. It rotates, checks to see if it is in place and passes the sequence to its neighbors.
There are many brilliant scientists, engineers, designers working on this project.
I think this project really reveals: Is this really scalable?
I mean, it took thousands of dollars a lot of people to build this eight-foot robot.
Can we really scale it up, can we really embed robots in every part?
The next question is to look at passiveness, or passively trying to make reorganization programmable.
But it goes a step further, and it tries to do the actual calculations.
Basically embedding the basic building blocks of most computing, the digital logic gates, go directly into the various parts.
This is the NAND gate.
There is one tetrahedron on each gate that you want to use for the calculation, and there are two input tetrahedra.
One of them is input from the user, like you're building bricks.
The other is the input of a brick placed before coming.
It then gives the output in 3D space.
This means that users stack bricks the way they want.
It calculates based on what has been done before and your instructions.
Now it starts to move in three dimensions - up or down.
Looking at the left, the input of [1,1] is equal to 0 output, indicating downward.
On the right, the input of [0,0] is 1 output, indicating up.
So what this really means is that our structure now contains the blueprints we want to build.
So the information about the thing you want to build is already all embedded in it.
This means we have some form of self-replication.
In this case, I call it self-directed replication, because you have an exact blueprint in your structure.
If you encounter an error, you can replace a section.
All the local information is embedded in it, telling you how to fix it.
So you have something you can climb, you can read it and output it one by one.
It is directly embedded; there is no external command input.
The last project I'm going to show is called an eccentric chain, and it's probably the most exciting example of a passive self-assembly system we're seeing right now.
Its reconfigurability and programmability make it a completely passive system.
Basically you have a chain of elements.
Each element is exactly the same, and they are eccentric.
Each chain, or each element, wants to turn right or left.
If you want to assemble the chain, you need to program it.
Tell each unit whether to turn left or right.
When you shake this chain, it folds up to program whatever structure you've coded for it -- so in this case, a spiral, in the case of fire, two connected cubes.
Basically you can program in three dimensions -- or one or two dimensions -- and the chain is completely passive.
What future does this foretell us?
I think this tells us about the possibilities of this self-assembly, self-replication and self-healing in our bodily structures, our buildings and machines.
There is new programmability in these sections.
From this you can get new possibilities for computation.
We will have spatial calculations.
Imagine our buildings, our bridges, our machines, all the bricks that do the actual calculations.
What an amazing parallel and distributed computing power and new design possibilities.
This is an exciting potential.
I think these projects that I'm showing you are just a small step into the future if we implement these new technologies for a new self-assembled world.
Thank you.
