Recently, we have seen the impact of cyberattacks on the business world.
Data breaches at companies like JPMorgan Chase, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target have cost hundreds of millions of dollars, if not billions of dollars.
A few more such attacks and the entire world economy would collapse.
The public sphere is not spared either.
From 2012 to 2014, the U.S. Office of Personnel Management had a very serious data breach.
Security clearances and fingerprint information were stolen, affecting 22 million employees.
You may have also heard that some government-sponsored hackers are trying to use stolen data to influence election results in some countries.
The last two are the massive data theft of the German Bundestag and the email theft of the Democratic National Committee in the United States.
Cyberthreats have affected our democratic process.
And there is a growing trend.
The more advanced computer technology is, the more vulnerable the means we use to protect data become.
In particular, a new type of computer technology, called a quantum computer, uses microscopic particles in nature to dramatically increase the computing power of computers.
It's computationally powerful enough to crack many of the encryption systems we use today.
So are we hopeless?
Should we start packing up our electronic survival gear for the coming data apocalypse?
I think it's not there yet.
Quantum computers only exist in the lab, and practical use is still years away.
What’s more, there have been many major breakthroughs in the crypto space.
For me, this is a very exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, I learned that we had unlocked new skills to create quantum effects that don't exist in nature, and I was very excited.
The idea of using the fundamental laws of physics to advance cryptography is exciting to me.
Today, a select group of companies and labs, including mine, have advanced this technology to the stage of practical application.
That's right.
We are going to fight quantum with quantum.
How to achieve it?
First, let’s take a quick look at the world of encryption.
You need a briefcase, and you have some important documents to give to your good friend, James Bond, to be locked up and kept safe.
Because these materials are top secret, we're going to use a super-advanced briefcase.
It comes with a special combination lock that, once locked, converts the contents of the file into random numbers.
So you just put the file in, lock it, and now the file has been converted to random numbers, and you give this briefcase to James.
Before the briefcase arrives, you call him and tell him the password.
Once he got the briefcase, he typed in the password, and the file was deciphered, it was perfect, and you successfully passed an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) It's a fun example, but it illustrates three important things about encryption.
Password - we call it an encryption key.
You can think of it like a password.
The phone that told James the password.
We call it key passing.
This ensures that we can safely deliver the key to the designated location.
and locks for encrypting and decrypting files.
We call it an encryption algorithm.
With the secret key, it converts the contents of the file into random numbers.
A good algorithm can do this, and it is difficult to crack the password without the secret key.
The importance of algorithms is that if someone gets a briefcase, opens it, and doesn't have the secret key and doesn't know the encryption algorithm, they can't read the contents of the document.
All you get is some random numbers.
Most security systems rely on secure key delivery to get the key to the right place.
However, rapidly increasing computing power jeopardizes many of the key delivery methods we currently use.
As an example, we have a very wide application of the system - RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it took about 4 quadrillion years to crack a 426-bit RSA key.
And in 1994, just 17 years later, the code was cracked.
As computers become more powerful, the passwords we need become longer and longer.
Now we often use 2048 or 4096-bit passwords.
As you can see, there's a battle going on between the encryptor and the decrypter, both trying to win the other.
In the next 10 to 15 years, the arrival of quantum computers will make it faster to crack the complex mathematical algorithms that are the basis of the encryption systems we use today.
In fact, quantum computers will turn our safe castle into a knock-down house of cards.
We will try to protect our castle.
In recent years, many research institutions have emerged to study how to use quantum effects to enhance encryption.
Some exciting breakthroughs have been made.
Remember the three key points of encryption: high-quality keys, secure key delivery, and strong algorithms.
However, advances in science and engineering have jeopardized two of these priorities.
The first is the secret key.
Random numbers are the basis of the secret key.
But today, they are no longer truly random.
Currently, we generate the secret key, which is generated by software based on the frequency of random numbers, which we call pseudo-random numbers.
The numbers generated by programs or mathematical methods will always have some, perhaps not so obvious rules in them.
The less random these numbers are, or in terminology, the lower the moisture they contain, the more predictable they are.
Recently, some casinos have been hacked in creative ways.
They shoot at the slot machine for a period of time and then analyze it.
Cybercriminals use reverse engineering to create the pseudo-random number generator behind the turntable.
So they have a good chance of predicting the turn of the wheel and making a lot of money.
The secret key is also insecure.
Having a truly random number generator is important for generating secure passwords.
For years, researchers have been trying to build a true random number generator.
But most designs are either not random enough, not fast enough, or difficult to reuse.
But the quantum world is truly random.
It’s important to take advantage of this true randomness.
Devices capable of measuring quantum effects can generate a continuous stream of random numbers very quickly.
The casino crime just mentioned is no longer possible.
Several universities and companies from around the world are concentrating on making true random number generators.
